{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17474198","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17474198"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:18:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:18:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11827"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11827","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11827"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.49,0.18,0.18,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4432"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51686"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4432","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4432"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11827"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36988"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"39"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"88"},{"type":"tags","id":"659"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"2316"},{"type":"tags","id":"3485"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6343"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6593"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13913"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14910"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42667"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44109"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44822"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51686","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/51686"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 20-month-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of shortness of breath. He has a medical history of one episode of acute otitis media in the previous month and five episodes of pneumonia in the past seven months. His maternal uncle died from a severe \u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus pneumoniae\u003C/em\u003E infection one year ago. He has no other significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 160/min, blood pressure 90/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 30/min, SpO2 94% on room air, and temperature 38.5\u00b0C. His height and weight are both tracking along the 50th centiles. Chest examination reveals decreased breath sounds in the right upper zone. Abdominal examination is normal. Oropharyngeal inspection reveals absent tonsils, but there is no history of tonsillectomy. A chest X-ray shows a well-defined consolidation in the right upper lung zone.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely underlying cause of this child\u0027s presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["IgA deficiency","X-linked agammaglobulinaemia","Wiskott-Aldrich syndrome","Severe combined immunodeficiency","Leukocyte adhesion deficiency"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis child\u0027s presentation strongly suggests an underlying primary immunodeficiency, specifically \u003Cstrong\u003EX-linked agammaglobulinaemia\u003C/strong\u003E (also known as Bruton\u0027s agammaglobulinaemia). The key features supporting this diagnosis are:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E1. Recurrent bacterial infections (pneumonia, otitis media) in a young male child\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E2. Family history of severe infection in a maternal uncle (X-linked inheritance pattern)\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E3. Absent tonsils without history of tonsillectomy (poor development of lymphoid tissue)\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E4. Infections with encapsulated bacteria (e.g., \u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus pneumoniae\u003C/em\u003E)\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIgA deficiency\u003C/strong\u003E is the most common primary immunodeficiency, but it typically presents with milder symptoms and cannot be definitively diagnosed until after age 4 when IgA levels reach adult levels. The severity and early onset of infections in this case make IgA deficiency less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWiskott-Aldrich syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is an X-linked disorder characterised by the triad of eczema, thrombocytopenia with small platelets, and recurrent infections. The absence of skin problems or bleeding issues makes this diagnosis unlikely in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESevere combined immunodeficiency (SCID)\u003C/strong\u003E affects both B and T cell function, leading to severe, recurrent infections with viruses, fungi, and opportunistic pathogens in addition to bacteria. SCID typically presents earlier in infancy and with more severe, life-threatening infections.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeukocyte adhesion deficiency\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by recurrent bacterial infections, impaired wound healing, and persistent leukocytosis. It typically presents in the neonatal period with delayed separation of the umbilical cord, which is not mentioned in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EX-linked agammaglobulinaemia is caused by mutations in the BTK gene, resulting in a lack of mature B cells and severe antibody deficiency. This explains the recurrent infections with encapsulated bacteria and the poorly developed lymphoid tissue (absent tonsils). Treatment typically involves lifelong immunoglobulin replacement therapy and prophylactic antibiotics.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["X-linked agammaglobulinaemia (Bruton\u0027s disease) is characterised by the absence of mature B cells, leading to severe antibody deficiency and recurrent infections, particularly with encapsulated bacteria.","Family history and recurrent bacterial infections in male infants should raise suspicion for X-linked agammaglobulinaemia.","Absent lymphoid tissue (e.g., tonsils) can be a clinical sign of X-linked agammaglobulinaemia."],"references":["Cardenas-Morales M, Hernandez-Trujillo VP. Agammaglobulinemia: from\u00a0X\u2011linked to\u00a0Autosomal Forms of\u00a0Disease. Clin Rev Allergy Immunol. 2022; 63: 22\u201335"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36988"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11827"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36988","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/36988"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-28T10:18:38+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-28T10:20:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4432"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51686"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links"